{"title_page": "Kane Tanaka", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese supercentenarian}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kane Tanaka\n| image              = \n| native_name        = \u7530\u4e2d\u30ab\u5b50\n| native_name_lang   = J\u00e2n \u0164an Na K\u00e4 in Religious Shintoism\nKh\u00e5n Ta\u00f1nak\u00e0 in Islamic\nKaan \u0164anak\u0113 in Judaism\nH\u00e4 Thannak\u00e0 in Hinduism\nKa\u00e3ne T\u00e6nuk\u00e0 in Kane's Religion\nK\u00f6\u00f6ne Tanaxha\u00e4xs in ????????????\nKunn\u00eb Tannk\u00e6 in Chinese Religion\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1903|1|2|df=y}}<br>(age {{age in years and days|1903|01|02|df=y}})\n| birth_place        = Wajiro Village (now [[Higashi-ku, Fukuoka|Higashi-ku]], [[Fukuoka]]), [[Fukuoka Prefecture]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]\n| nationality        = [[Japanese people|Japanese]]\n| known_for          = Oldest living person <br/> (22 July 2018 \u2013 present)\n| parents            = Kumakichi and Kuma Ota\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Hideo Tanaka|6 January 1922}}\n| children           = 5 (4 biological, 1 adopted)\n| relatives          = \n| title              = \n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Kane Tanaka'''|\u7530\u4e2d\u30ab\u5b50|Tanaka Kane|born 2 January 1903}} is a validated Japanese [[supercentenarian]] who, at age {{Age in years and days|1903|1|2}}, is the world's oldest [[List of the oldest living people|verified living person]] following the death of 117-year-old Chiyo Miyako on 22 July 2018.<ref name=\"GRG\">{{cite web |url=http://www.grg.org/Adams/TableE.html |title=Validated Living Supercentenarians |website=grg.org |publisher=[[Gerontology Research Group]] |date=19 October 2017 |access-date=20 October 2017}} The Gerontology Research Group (GRG) lists people as living whose age has been validated and confirmed to be alive within the past year.</ref> She is the eighth verified oldest person ever.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Kane Tanaka 117.jpg|thumb|Kane Tanaka, of 117 years old (2020)]]\n[[File:Kane Tanaka3.jpg|left|thumb|252x252px|Young Kane Tanaka on the middle, about 20 years old]]\nTanaka was born on 2 January 1903, the seventh child to Kumakichi and Kuma Ota in the village of Wajiro (now part of [[Higashi-ku, Fukuoka|Higashi-ku]], [[Fukuoka]]), [[Fukuoka Prefecture]], [[Japan]], on the southern island of [[Kyushu]].<ref name=asahi-20180727 /> Born in the waning years of the [[Meiji (era)|Meiji era]], Tanaka was [[Preterm birth|premature]] and raised on breast milk from [[wet nurse|nurses]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20180728/k00/00m/040/039000c |script-title=ja:\u7530\u4e2d\u30ab\u5b50\u3055\u3093\uff11\uff11\uff15\u6b73\u300c-\u6b7b\u306c\u6c17\u5168\u7136\u305b\u3093\u3067\u3059\u300d |language=ja |trans-title=Japan's oldest woman, Kanako Tanaka, at 115: \"I do not feel like dying at all\" |newspaper=[[Mainichi Shimbun]] |first=Masashi |last=Hoda |date=27 July 2018 |access-date=10 November 2018 |url-access= subscription}}</ref> During [[World War II]], she worked in a store selling [[Shiruko]] and [[Udon|udon noodles]] with her husband Hideo, whom she married in 1922. After Hideo and her son died during the war, she continued working in the store before [[Retirement|retiring]] at the age of 63.<ref name=asahi-20180727>{{cite news |url=https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASL7W3QJRL7WTIPE00K.html |script-title=ja:\u56fd\u5185\u6700\u9ad8\u9f62\uff11\uff11\uff15\u6b73\u3001\u5165\u6240\u8005\u52b1\u307e\u3059\u300c\u9811\u5f35\u308a\u3093\u3057\u3083\u3044\u300d |language=ja |trans-title=At 115, the oldest man in Japan advises citizens to \"try hard\" |newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]] |first=Toshihiro |last=Kashiwagi |date=27 July 2018 |access-date=10 November 2018}}</ref> Kane and Hideo had 4 biological children and adopted a 5th child.<ref name=\"guinness-2019\"/> In the 1970s, she visited the [[United States]], where she has several nieces and nephews.<ref name=\"SDUT\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-113-year-old-kane-tanaka-supercentenarian-2016may06-story.html |title=San Marcos couple celebrate aunt's 113th year |newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]] |first=Linda |last=McIntosh |date=6 June 2016 |accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt age 103, Tanaka was diagnosed with [[Colorectal cancer|colon cancer]].<ref name=asahi-20180727 /> When she was 107, her son wrote a book about her, which discusses her life and longevity and is titled ''In Good and Bad Times, 107 Years Old''. She was interviewed by [[Kyushu Asahi Broadcasting|KBC]] in September 2017 when she was 114.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kbc.co.jp/asadesu/asadesutv/detail.html?id=5861 |title=\u5143\u6c17\u306b\u9577\u751f\u304d\u3059\u308b\u79d8\u3051\u3064 |language=ja |trans-title=The secret to a healthy long life |publisher=[[Kyushu Asahi Broadcasting|KBC]] |date=19 September 2017 |access-date=10 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810205954/http://www.kbc.co.jp/asadesu/asadesutv/detail.html?id=5861 |archive-date=10 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt the time of Chiyo Miyako\u2019s death, Tanaka lived in a hospital in the [[Higashi-ku, Fukuoka|Higashi-ku]] ward of [[Fukuoka]], Fukuoka Prefecture. She was still in good health and occupied her time by playing the board game [[Reversi|Othello]] and taking short walks in the facility's hallways.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/07/26/national/japans-oldest-person-chiyo-miyako-dies-117/#.W1naweSWy70 |title=Japan's oldest person Chiyo Miyako dies at 117 |agency=Kyodo |work=The Japan Times |date=27 July 2018 |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref> Her hobbies include [[calligraphy]] and [[calculation]]s.<ref name=Sankei /> She credits family, sleep and hope as her secrets for [[longevity]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/who-worlds-oldest-person-miyako-chiyo-dies-117-passing-title-kane-tanaka-1044901 |title=Who is the World's oldest Person? Chiyo Miyako Dies At 117, Passing Title To Kane Tanaka |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |first=David |last=Brennan |date=27 July 2018 |access-date=27 July 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, she said she would like to live another five years to the age of 120.<ref name=asahi-20180727 />\n\nTanaka has a strong appetite and likes [[Candy|sweets]]; she drinks three cans a day of [[canned coffee]], [[carbonated drink|sodas]], and various nutritional drinks.<ref name=asahi-20180727 /><ref name=Sankei>{{cite news |url=https://www.sankei.com/west/news/180727/wst1807270057-n1.html |script-title=ja:\uff11\uff11\uff15\u6b73\u56fd\u5185\u6700\u9ad8\u9f62\u306e\u7530\u4e2d\u30ab\u5b50\u3055\u3093\u300c\u307f\u3093\u306a\u306e\u304a\u304b\u3052\u300d\u3068\u611f\u8b1d\u3000\u30ab\u30d5\u30a7\u30aa\u30ec\u6bce\u65e5\uff13\u3001\uff14\u672c |language=ja |trans-title=Oldest person in the country, Kane Tanaka, 115, says \"thanks to everyone\" and enjoys 3 or 4 ''[[caf\u00e9 au lait]]'' every day |newspaper=[[Sankei Shimbun]] |date=27 July 2018 |access-date=9 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2019, she was recognised as the World's Oldest Living Person by [[Guinness World Records]].<ref name=\"guinness-2019\">{{cite web |last=Senda |first=Masakazu |url=https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2019/3/worlds-oldest-person-confirmed-as-116-year-old-kane-tanaka-from-japan |title=World's oldest person confirmed as 116-year-old Kane Tanaka from Japan |work=[[Guinness World Records]] |date=9 March 2019 |accessdate=11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Japanese supercentenarians]]\n*[[List of the verified oldest people]]\n*[[Oldest people]]\n*[[Supercentenarian]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.telegraphherald.com/news/national_world/article_6329f3f4-593f-5121-bf20-86c23e93f233.html ''Telegraph Herald'' News in brief]\n*[http://image.honto.jp/item/1/265/0328/1953/03281953_1.png Honto \"In Good and Bad Times, 107 Years Old\"]\n* [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/07/27/life-expectancies-2018-japan-switzerland-spain/848675002/ ''USA Today'' What countries have the longest life expectancies?]\n* [https://www.sfchronicle.com/world/article/News-of-the-day-from-around-the-globe-July-27-13111661.php ''San Francisco Chronicle'' News of the day from around the globe, July 27]\n* [https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/nation-and-world/worlds-oldest-person-dies-at-117-now-115-year-old-is-oldest/ ''Las Vegas Review-Journal'' World\u2019s oldest person dies at 117, now 115-year-old is oldest]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tanaka, Kane}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colorectal cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Female supercentenarians]]\n[[Category:Japanese supercentenarians]]\n[[Category:People from Fukuoka]]\n[[Category:People of Meiji-period Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese supercentenarian}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kane Tanaka\n| image              = \n| native_name        = \u7530\u4e2d\u30ab\u5b50\n| native_name_lang   = J\u00e2n \u0164an Na K\u00e4 in Religious\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1903|1|2|df=y}}<br>(age {{age in years and days|1903|01|02|df=y}})\n| birth_place        = Wajiro Village (now [[Higashi-ku, Fukuoka|Higashi-ku]], [[Fukuoka]]), [[Fukuoka Prefecture]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]\n| nationality        = [[Japanese people|Japanese]]\n| known_for          = Oldest living person <br/> (22 July 2018 \u2013 present)\n| parents            = Kumakichi and Kuma Ota\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Hideo Tanaka|6 January 1922}}\n| children           = 5 (4 biological, 1 adopted)\n| relatives          = \n| title              = \n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Kane Tanaka'''|\u7530\u4e2d\u30ab\u5b50|Tanaka Kane|born 2 January 1903}} is a validated Japanese [[supercentenarian]] who, at age {{Age in years and days|1903|1|2}}, is the world's oldest [[List of the oldest living people|verified living person]] following the death of 117-y